---
title: Sweet Ginger Salmon with Buttery Rice & Roasted Green Beans
description: Pork chops are always a weeknight winner. They’re satisfying, speedy, and versatile, which is why our chefs are always brainstorming new ways to take ’em to the next level. The kicker this week: a fresh ginger and apricot jam pan sauce to drizzle over the chops. On the side, there’s roasted green beans and buttery jasmine rice (perfect for catching any runoff sauce).
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/6422f9ce964b8ed6a409d9f1-94675d8a.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/658c73d90b6b7b8902a601a4.pdf
course: main course
cuisine: Asian
time required: 35 minutes
servings: 2
nutrition:
  calories: 810 kcal
  fat: 47 g
  saturated fat: 13 g
  carbohydrates: 59 g
  sugar: 15 g
  protein: 34 g
  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 280 mg
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/sweet-ginger-salmon-658c73d90b6b7b8902a601a4
author: HelloFresh
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}. Trim @green beans{6%ounce} if necessary.
Thinly slice @chili pepper{1}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a small #pot over medium-high
heat. Add half the ginger and cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, 3/4 cup water, and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a
boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender,
~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, toss green beans on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of oil and
a big pinch of salt and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pat @skin-on salmon{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season with
salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a medium #pan over medium-high heat. Add salmon and cook
until browned and cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes} per side.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{}. Wipe out pan.

> Swap in chicken or salmon for pork. Cook chicken until cooked through, 3-5
> minutes per side, or cook salmon (skin sides down) until skin is crisp, 5-7
> minutes, then flip and cook until cooked through, 1-2 minutes more.

In a small #bowl, combine @apricot jam{1}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and
1/4 cup water.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for salmon over medium heat. Add remaining
ginger and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in jam mixture and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove from heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Season with salt
and pepper.

> Use pan used for chicken or salmon here.

Thinly slice salmon crosswise.

Fluff rice with a #fork; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} and season with salt and
pepper.

Divide rice and green beans between plates. Top rice with salmon and drizzle
with sauce. Garnish with chili to taste and serve.

> Thinly slice chicken crosswise (skip slicing salmon!).

> Salmon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.